(42, 10, 38, 63, 1, 10, 10, 'received him into her house', 'Hospitality and Reception', 'This connection highlights the theme of hospitality in both passages. In Luke 10:38, Martha receives Jesus into her house, while 2 John 1:10 advises against receiving those who do not bring the correct doctrine.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 39, 20, 8, 34, 34, NULL, 'Listening and Waiting for Wisdom', 'This connection highlights the importance of attentiveness to wisdom. Both passages emphasize the act of listening—Mary at Jesus'' feet and the blessed man who hears and waits at wisdom''s gates.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 39, 42, 8, 35, 35, NULL, 'Sitting at Jesus'' Feet', 'This connection highlights the act of sitting at Jesus'' feet, which signifies a posture of learning and receiving His teachings. Both Mary and the healed man are depicted in this position, emphasizing their devotion and transformation through Jesus'' presence.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 39, 43, 12, 3, 3, 'sat at Jesus’ feet', 'Mary''s Devotion to Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize Mary''s actions at Jesus'' feet, highlighting her devotion and attentiveness. In Luke, she listens to His words, while in John, she anoints His feet, demonstrating her reverence.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 39, 44, 22, 3, 3, 'sat at Jesus’ feet', 'Teaching and Learning at Feet', 'This connection highlights the act of sitting at the feet of a teacher, as seen in both passages. Mary sits at Jesus'' feet to learn, while Paul mentions being brought up at the feet of Gamaliel, indicating a similar posture of learning and discipleship.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 39, 5, 33, 3, 3, 'sat at Jesus’ feet', 'Sitting at Jesus'' Feet', 'This connection highlights the act of sitting at the feet of a teacher to receive wisdom. Both passages emphasize the importance of being in a position to hear and receive words of instruction.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 39, 42, 2, 46, 46, 'sat at Jesus’ feet, and heard', 'Sitting and Hearing', 'This connection highlights the act of sitting and hearing in both passages. Mary sits at Jesus'' feet to hear his word, while Jesus sits in the temple to hear and ask questions.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 39, 46, 7, 32, 40, 'sat at Jesus’ feet', 'Focus on Spiritual Matters', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of prioritizing spiritual pursuits over worldly concerns. In Luke, Mary sits at Jesus'' feet to hear his word, while in 1 Corinthians, the unmarried are encouraged to care for the things of the Lord without distraction.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 40, 43, 6, 27, 27, 'much serving', 'Service and Spiritual Nourishment', 'This connection highlights the contrast between physical labor and spiritual sustenance. Martha''s concern for serving reflects the earthly focus, while Jesus emphasizes seeking ''meat which endureth unto everlasting life.''', 'theme', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 40, 42, 12, 29, 29, 'cumbered about much serving', 'Concern for Daily Needs', 'This connection highlights the theme of worry over daily provisions. Martha''s concern for serving reflects a preoccupation with physical needs, which is echoed in the admonition against seeking what to eat or drink.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 40, 40, 14, 15, 15, 'serve alone', 'Service and Provision Themes', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of serving others and the need for provision. Martha expresses concern over serving alone, while the disciples highlight the need for food for the multitude. This connection highlights the importance of addressing both spiritual and physical needs.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 40, 40, 16, 22, 22, 'Lord, dost thou not care', 'Concern for Service and Duty', 'This connection highlights a theme of concern for duty and service. In both passages, characters express a sense of urgency and responsibility, with Martha feeling burdened by her tasks and Peter rebuking Jesus out of concern for his mission.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 40, 32, 4, 1, 4, 'Lord, dost thou not care', 'Anger and Service Discontent', 'This connection highlights the theme of discontent in service and anger towards others. Both Martha and Jonah express frustration over perceived unfairness in their situations, leading to a plea for intervention.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 40, 41, 3, 21, 21, 'dost thou not care', 'Concern for Jesus'' Well-being', 'This connection highlights the theme of concern for Jesus'' state. In Luke, Martha expresses worry about her sister''s lack of help, while in Mark, friends are concerned that Jesus is ''beside himself.'' Both passages reflect a preoccupation with Jesus'' well-being.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 40, 42, 9, 55, 55, 'cumbered about much serving', 'Spirit of Service and Reprimand', 'This connection highlights the theme of service and the spirit behind actions. Martha''s complaint about her sister''s lack of help reflects a misunderstanding of priorities, similar to the rebuke in Luke 9:55 regarding the spirit of the disciples.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 41, 50, 4, 6, 6, 'careful and troubled about many things', 'Concern and Prayer Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of being ''careful'' or anxious. Both passages address the issue of worry, with Luke emphasizing Martha''s troubles and Philippians encouraging believers to avoid anxiety through prayer.', 'theme', 0.496, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 41, 41, 4, 19, 19, 'careful and troubled about many things', 'Connection of Worldly Cares', 'Both passages emphasize being ''careful and troubled'' by worldly concerns. This connection highlights how such distractions can hinder spiritual growth and fruitfulness.', 'theme', 0.43999999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 41, 40, 6, 25, 34, 'careful and troubled about many things', 'Concerns About Daily Needs', 'Both passages emphasize being ''careful and troubled'' about daily needs. They encourage trust in God for provision rather than anxiety over material concerns.', 'theme', 0.43299999999999994, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 41, 42, 21, 34, 34, 'careful and troubled about many things', 'Cares of Life Connection', 'Both passages emphasize being troubled by cares of life. Martha''s concern reflects the dangers of being overcharged with life''s distractions, as warned in Luke 21:34.', 'theme', 0.43299999999999994, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 41, 42, 8, 14, 14, 'careful and troubled about many things', 'Connection of Cares and Troubles', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of being overwhelmed by cares. In Luke 10:41, Martha is described as ''careful and troubled,'' while Luke 8:14 mentions being ''choked with cares.'' This connection highlights the spiritual dangers of being consumed by worldly concerns.', 'theme', 0.419, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 41, 46, 7, 32, 35, 'careful and troubled about many things', 'Concern and Distraction in Service', 'This connection highlights the theme of being ''careful'' or distracted by worldly concerns in both passages. Martha is admonished for being troubled about many things, while Paul encourages the unmarried to focus on pleasing the Lord without distraction.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 41, 21, 6, 11, 11, 'careful and troubled about many things', 'Concerns and Vanity in Life', 'This connection highlights the theme of being troubled by many things, as seen in Martha''s anxiety in Luke, and the acknowledgment of vanity in Ecclesiastes. Both passages emphasize the futility of excessive concern and the search for meaning amidst life''s distractions.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 42, 19, 27, 4, 4, 'one thing is needful', 'Desire for God''s Presence', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of seeking a singular focus on God. Mary chooses the good part, while the psalmist desires to dwell in the house of the Lord.', 'theme', 0.622, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 42, 19, 16, 5, 6, 'good part', 'Inheritance and Good Choices', 'Both passages emphasize the idea of choosing what is good and valuable. Mary’s choice of the ''good part'' parallels the psalmist''s declaration of the Lord as his ''portion'' and ''inheritance.''', 'theme', 0.538, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 42, 43, 10, 27, 28, 'good part', 'Eternal Life and Good Choices', 'This connection highlights the importance of choosing what is eternal and valuable. Mary’s choice of the ''good part'' parallels the promise of eternal life in John, emphasizing the lasting significance of following Jesus.', 'theme', 0.517, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 42, 43, 4, 14, 14, 'that good part', 'Connection of Spiritual Nourishment', 'This connection highlights the theme of choosing what is spiritually essential. Both passages emphasize the importance of selecting the ''good part'' and the ''water'' that leads to everlasting life.', 'theme', 0.489, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 42, 42, 18, 22, 22, 'one thing is needful', 'The Importance of Choosing Wisely', 'Both passages emphasize the necessity of prioritizing spiritual over material wealth. Mary chooses the ''good part,'' while the rich young ruler is told he lacks ''one thing'' to follow Jesus fully.', 'theme', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 42, 41, 8, 36, 36, 'good part', 'Value of Spiritual Choices', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of prioritizing spiritual well-being over worldly gains. Mary chooses the ''good part,'' while the warning in Mark highlights the futility of gaining the world at the expense of one''s soul.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 42, 5, 30, 19, 19, 'chosen that good part', 'Choosing Life and Goodness', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of making a conscious choice for what is good. Mary chooses the ''good part,'' while Deuteronomy urges the choice of life over death.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
